04082nam a22005175i 9780822393313DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20102010ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223933137 a10.1515/97808223933132doi  a(DE-B1597)553444  a(OCoLC)709617223  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0520002bisacsh04a3062221 aGrossberg, Lawrence, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCultural Studies in the Future Tense /cLawrence Grossberg. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2010] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (370 p.) :b2 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tThanks -- tIntroduction: We All Want to Change the World -- tOne. The Heart of Cultural Studies -- tTwo. Constructing the Conjuncture: Struggling over Modernity -- tThree. Considering Value: Rescuing Economies from Economists -- tFour. Contextualizing Culture: Mediation, Signification, and Significance -- tFive. Complicating Power: The "And" of Politics, and . . . -- tSix. In Search of Modernities -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLawrence Grossberg is one of the leading figures in cultural studies internationally. In Cultural Studies in the Future Tense, he offers a powerful critique of the present state of cultural studies and, more broadly, of the intellectual left, especially in the Anglo-American academy. He develops a vision for the future of cultural studies as conjunctural analysis, a radically contingent and contextual study of the articulations of lived, discursive, and material contexts. Proposing a compelling analysis of the contemporary political problem space as a struggle over modernity, he suggests the possibility of multiple ways of being modern as an analytic and imaginative frame. He elaborates an ontology of the modern as the potentialities of multiple configurations of temporalities and spatialities, differences, territorialities, and powers, and argues that euro-modernity is a specific geohistorical realization of this complex diagram. Challenging the euro-modern fragmentation of the social formation, he discusses the rigorous conceptual and empirical work that cultural studies must do-including rethinking fundamental concepts such as economy, culture, and politics as well as modernity-to reinvent itself as an effective political intellectual project. This book offers a vision of a contemporary cultural studies that embraces complexity, rigorous interdisciplinary practice and experimental collaborations in an effort to better explain the present in the service of the imagination of other futures and the struggles for social transformation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCulturexStudy and teaching. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822393313zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822393313423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822393313/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles